1. 21. quaesitor] The criminal courts of Rome, after their final organisation by Sulla's lex Cornelia, were named quaestiones perpetuae, ‘ standing commissions of enquiry.' The duty of the Jud ge (quaesitor) was to preside and to regulate the proceedings in terms of the law under which he acted. The duty of the Jury (who as a body were termed consilium, while the individual members of the panel were called iudices) was, aster hearing the pleadings and the evidence, to pronounce upon the guilt or innocence of the accused.
